<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1912-09-24T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1912-09-24T00:00:00-05:00" n="1389" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1389">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 412.11/137.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">American Ambassador</gloss> to
                                the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi>.</head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 400.]</seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">American Embassy</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Mexico</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-09-24">
                                    <hi rend="italic">September 24, 1912</hi></date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>: I have the honor to report that acting
                            upon certain representations made by Mr. A. W. Heaton, one of the El
                            Paso claimants against the Mexican Government, an inquiry was made at
                            the Mexican Foreign Office as to the present status of the El Paso
                            claims for damages growing out of the injuries inflicted by firing
                            across the line from the Mexican side to the American side of the
                            boundary, and that Mr. Lascurain replied that the claimants without
                            exception had refused to enter into negotiations, preferring to await
                            the action of the joint Senate and House-Committee appointed by Congress
                            to investigate into the matter.</p>
                        <p>I have [etc.]</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Henry Lane Wilson.</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>